#: grub2.xml:129
#, no-c-format
msgid "/etc/grub.d/"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: grub2.xml:130
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"The scripts in this directory are read during execution of the <xref linkend="
"\"vle.grub2.mkconfig\"/> command. Their instructions are integrated into the "
"main configuration file <filename>/boot/grub/grub.cfg</filename>."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: filename
#: grub2.xml:139
#, no-c-format
msgid "/etc/sysconfig/bootloader"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: secondary
#: grub2.xml:143
#, no-c-format
msgid "sysconfig/bootloader"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: grub2.xml:144
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"This configuration file is used when configuring the boot loader with &yast; "
"and every time a new kernel is installed. It is evaluated by the perl-"
"bootloader which modifies the boot loader configuration file (for example "
"<filename>/boot/grub2/grub.cfg</filename> for &grub;) accordingly. "
"<filename>/etc/sysconfig/bootloader</filename> is not a &grub;-specific "
"configuration file&mdash;the values are applied to any boot loader installed "
"on &productname;."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: term
#: grub2.xml:156
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"<filename arch=\"x86_64\">/boot/grub2/x86_64-efi</filename>, <filename arch="
"\"power\">/boot/grub2/power-ieee1275</filename>, <filename arch=\"zseries\">/"
"boot/grub2/s390x</filename>"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: grub2.xml:161
#, no-c-format
msgid "These configuration files contain architecture-specific options."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: grub2.xml:168
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"&grub; can be controlled in various ways. Boot entries from an existing "
"configuration can be selected from the graphical menu (splash screen). The "
"configuration is loaded from the file <filename>/boot/grub2/grub.cfg</"
"filename> which is compiled from other configuration files (see below). All "
"&grub; configuration files are considered system files, and you need "
"&rootuser; privileges to edit them."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: title
#: grub2.xml:178
#, no-c-format
msgid "Activating Configuration Changes"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: grub2.xml:179
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"After having manually edited &grub; configuration files, you need to run "
"<xref linkend=\"vle.grub2.mkconfig\"/> to activate the changes. However, "
"this is not necessary when changing the configuration with &yast;, since it "
"will automatically run <xref linkend=\"vle.grub2.mkconfig\"/>."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: title
#: grub2.xml:188
#, no-c-format
msgid "The File <filename>/boot/grub2/grub.cfg</filename>"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: primary
#: grub2.xml:189 grub2.xml:220
#, no-c-format
msgid "configuration files"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: secondary
#: grub2.xml:192
#, no-c-format
msgid "boot menu"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: grub2.xml:195
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"The graphical splash screen with the boot menu is based on the &grub; "
"configuration file <filename>/boot/grub2/grub.cfg</filename>, which contains "
"information about all partitions or operating systems that can be booted by "
"the menu."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: grub2.xml:201
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"Every time the system is booted, &grub; loads the menu file directly from "
"the file system. For this reason, &grub; does not need to be re-installed "
"after changes to the configuration file. <filename>grub.cfg</filename> is "
"automatically rebuilt with kernel installations or removals."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: grub2.xml:207
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"<filename>grub.cfg</filename> is compiled by the <xref linkend=\"vle.grub2."
"mkconfig\"/> from the file <filename>/etc/default/grub</filename> and "
"scripts found in the <filename>/etc/grub.d/</filename> directory. Therefore "
"you should never edit the file manually. Instead, edit the related source "
"files or use the &yast; <guimenu>Boot Loader</guimenu> module to modify the "
"configuration as described in <xref linkend=\"sec.grub2.yast2.config\"/>."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: title
#: grub2.xml:219
#, no-c-format
msgid "The File <filename>/etc/default/grub</filename>"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: grub2.xml:224
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"More general options of &grub; belong here, such as the time the menu is "
"displayed, or the default OS to boot. To list all available options, see the "
"output of the following command:"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: screen
#: grub2.xml:229
#, no-c-format
msgid "grep \"export GRUB_DEFAULT\" -A50 /usr/sbin/grub2-mkconfig | grep GRUB_"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: grub2.xml:230
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"In addition to already defined variables, the user may introduce their own "
"variables, and use them later in the scripts found in the <filename>/etc/"
"grub.d</filename> directory."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: grub2.xml:235
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"After having edited <filename>/etc/default/grub</filename>, run <xref "
"linkend=\"vle.grub2.mkconfig\"/> to update the main configuration file."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: title
#: grub2.xml:240
#, no-c-format
msgid "Scope"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: grub2.xml:241
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"All options set in this file are general options that affect all boot "
"entries. Specific options for &xen; Kernels or the &xen; hypervisor can be "
"set via the GRUB_*_XEN_* configuration options. See below for details."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: literal
#: grub2.xml:249
#, no-c-format
msgid "GRUB_DEFAULT"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: grub2.xml:252
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"Sets the boot menu entry that is booted by default. Its value can be a "
"numeric value, the complete name of a menu entry, or <quote>saved</quote>."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: grub2.xml:257
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"<literal>GRUB_DEFAULT=2</literal> boots the third (counted from zero) boot "
"menu entry."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: grub2.xml:261
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"<literal>GRUB_DEFAULT=\"2&gt;0\"</literal> boots the first submenu entry of "
"the third top-level menu entry."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: grub2.xml:265
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"<literal>GRUB_DEFAULT=\"Example boot menu entry\"</literal> boots the menu "
"entry with the title <quote>Example boot menu entry</quote>."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: grub2.xml:269
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"<literal>GRUB_DEFAULT=saved</literal> boots the entry specified by the "
"<command>grub2-reboot </command> or <command>grub2-set-default </command> "
"commands. While <command>grub2-reboot</command> sets the default boot entry "
"for the next reboot only, <command>grub2-set-default</command> sets the "
"default boot entry until changed."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: literal
#: grub2.xml:280
#, no-c-format
msgid "GRUB_HIDDEN_TIMEOUT"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: grub2.xml:283
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"Waits the specified number of seconds for the user to press a key. During "
"the period no menu is shown unless the user presses a key. If no key is "
"pressed during the time specified, the control is passed to "
"<literal>GRUB_TIMEOUT</literal>. <literal>GRUB_HIDDEN_TIMEOUT=0</literal> "
"first checks whether <keycap function=\"shift\"></keycap> is pressed and "
"shows the boot menu if yes, otherwise immediately boots the default menu "
"entry. This is the default when only one bootable OS is identified by &grub;."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: literal
#: grub2.xml:296
#, no-c-format
msgid "GRUB_HIDDEN_TIMEOUT_QUIET"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: grub2.xml:299
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"If <literal>false</literal> is specified, a countdown timer is displayed on "
"a blank screen when the <literal>GRUB_HIDDEN_TIMEOUT</literal> feature is "
"active."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: literal
#: grub2.xml:307
#, no-c-format
msgid "GRUB_TIMEOUT"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: grub2.xml:310
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"Time period in seconds the boot menu is displayed before automatically "
"booting the default boot entry. If you press a key, the timeout is cancelled "
"and &grub; waits for you to make the selection manually. "
"<literal>GRUB_TIMEOUT=-1</literal> will cause the menu to be displayed until "
"you select the boot entry manually."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: literal
#: grub2.xml:320
#, no-c-format
msgid "GRUB_CMDLINE_LINUX"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: grub2.xml:323
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"Entries on this line are added at the end of the boot entries for normal and "
"recovery mode. Use it to add kernel parameters to the boot entry."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: literal
#: grub2.xml:330
#, no-c-format
msgid "GRUB_CMDLINE_LINUX_DEFAULT"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: grub2.xml:333
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"Same as <literal>GRUB_CMDLINE_LINUX</literal> but the entries are appended "
"in the normal mode only."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: literal
#: grub2.xml:340
#, no-c-format
msgid "GRUB_CMDLINE_LINUX_RECOVERY"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: grub2.xml:343
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"Same as <literal>GRUB_CMDLINE_LINUX</literal> but the entries are appended "
"in the recovery mode only."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: literal
#: grub2.xml:350
#, no-c-format
msgid "GRUB_CMDLINE_LINUX_XEN_REPLACE"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: grub2.xml:353
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"This entry will completely replace the <literal>GRUB_CMDLINE_LINUX</literal> "
"parameters for all &xen; boot entries."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: literal
#: grub2.xml:361
#, no-c-format
msgid "GRUB_CMDLINE_LINUX_XEN_REPLACE_DEFAULT"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: grub2.xml:364
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"Same as <literal>GRUB_CMDLINE_LINUX_XEN_REPLACE</literal> but it will only "
"replace parameters of<literal>GRUB_CMDLINE_LINUX_DEFAULT</literal>."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: literal
#: grub2.xml:371
#, no-c-format
msgid "GRUB_CMDLINE_XEN"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: grub2.xml:374
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"This entry specifies the kernel parameters for the &xen; guest kernel "
"only&mdash;the operation principle is the same as for "
"<literal>GRUB_CMDLINE_LINUX</literal>."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: literal
#: grub2.xml:382
#, no-c-format
msgid "GRUB_CMDLINE_XEN_DEFAULT"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: grub2.xml:385
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"Same as <literal>GRUB_CMDLINE_XEN</literal>&mdash;the operation principle is "
"the same as for <literal>GRUB_CMDLINE_LINUX_DEFAULT</literal>."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: literal
#: grub2.xml:393
#, no-c-format
msgid "GRUB_TERMINAL"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: grub2.xml:396
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"Enables and specifies an input/output terminal device. Can be "
"<literal>console</literal> (PC BIOS and EFI consoles), <literal>serial</"
"literal> (serial terminal), <literal>ofconsole</literal> (Open Firmware "
"console), or the default <literal>gfxterm</literal> (graphics-mode output). "
"It is also possible to enable more than one device by quoting the required "
"options, for example <literal>GRUB_TERMINAL=\"console serial\"</literal>."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: literal
#: grub2.xml:408
#, no-c-format
msgid "GRUB_GFXMODE"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: grub2.xml:411
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"The resolution used for the <literal>gfxterm</literal> graphical terminal. "
"Note that you can only use modes supported by your graphics card (VBE). The "
"default is ‘auto’, which tries to select a preferred resolution. You can "
"display the screen resolutions available to &grub; by typing "
"<command>vbeinfo</command> in the &grub; command line. The command line is "
"accessed by typing <keycap>C</keycap> when the &grub; boot menu screen is "
"displayed."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: grub2.xml:420
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"You can also specify a color depth by appending it to the resolution "
"setting, for example <literal>GRUB_GFXMODE=1280x1024x24</literal>."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: literal
#: grub2.xml:427
#, no-c-format
msgid "GRUB_BACKGROUND"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: grub2.xml:430
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"Set a background image for the <literal>gfxterm</literal> graphical "
"terminal. The image must be a file readable by &grub; at boot time, and it "
"must end with the <literal>.png</literal>, <literal>.tga</literal>, "
"<literal>.jpg</literal>, or <literal>.jpeg</literal> suffix. If necessary, "
"the image will be scaled to fit the screen."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: literal
#: grub2.xml:440
#, no-c-format
msgid "GRUB_DISABLE_OS_PROBER"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: grub2.xml:443
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"If this option is set to <literal>true</literal>, automatic searching for "
"other operating systems is disabled. Only the kernel images in <filename>/"
"boot/</filename> and the options from your own scripts in <filename>/etc/"
"grub.d/</filename> are detected."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: literal
#: grub2.xml:452
#, no-c-format
msgid "SUSE_BTRFS_SNAPSHOT_BOOTING"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: grub2.xml:455
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"If this option is set to <literal>true</literal>, &grub; can boot directly "
"into Snapper snapshots. For more information, see <xref linkend=\"sec."
"snapper.snapshot-boot\"/>."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: title
#: grub2.xml:464
#, no-c-format
msgid "Parameter Handling"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: grub2.xml:465
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"All <literal>*_DEFAULT</literal> parameters can be configured manually or "
"with &yast;."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: grub2.xml:470
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"For a complete list of options, see the <link xlink:href=\"http://www.gnu."
"org/software/grub/manual/grub.html#Simple-configuration\"> GNU GRUB manual</"
"link>. For a complete list of possible parameters, see <link xlink:href="
"\"http://en.opensuse.org/Linuxrc\"></link>."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: title
#: grub2.xml:479
#, no-c-format
msgid "Scripts in <filename>/etc/grub.d</filename>"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: grub2.xml:480
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"The scripts in this directory are read during execution of the <xref linkend="
"\"vle.grub2.mkconfig\"/> command, and their instructions are incorporated "
"into <filename>/boot/grub2/grub.cfg</filename>. The order of menu items in "
"<filename>grub.cfg</filename> is determined by the order in which the files "
"in this directory are run. Files with a leading numeral are executed first, "
"beginning with the lowest number. <filename>00_header</filename> is run "
"before <filename>10_linux</filename>, which would run before "
"<filename>40_custom</filename>. If files with alphabetic names are present, "
"they are executed after the numerically-named files. Only executable files "
"generate output to <filename>grub.cfg</filename> during execution of "
"<command>grub2-mkconfig</command>. By default all files in the <filename>/"
"etc/grub.d</filename> directory are executable. The most important scripts "
"are:"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: filename
#: grub2.xml:498
#, no-c-format
msgid "00_header"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: grub2.xml:501
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"Sets environmental variables such as system file locations, display "
"settings, themes, and previously saved entries. It also imports preferences "
"stored in the <filename>/etc/default/grub</filename>. Normally you do not "
"need to make changes to this file."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: filename
#: grub2.xml:510
#, no-c-format
msgid "10_linux"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: grub2.xml:513
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"Identifies Linux kernels on the root device and creates relevant menu "
"entries. This includes the associated recovery mode option if enabled. Only "
"the latest kernel is displayed on the main menu page, with additional "
"kernels included in a submenu."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: filename
#: grub2.xml:522
#, no-c-format
msgid "30_os-prober"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: grub2.xml:525
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"This script uses <command>OS-prober</command> to search for Linux and other "
"operating systems and places the results in the &grub; menu. There are "
"sections to identify specific other operating systems, such as Windows or "
"macOS."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: filename
#: grub2.xml:534
#, no-c-format
msgid "40_custom"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: grub2.xml:537
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"This file provides a simple way to include custom boot entries into "
"<filename>grub.cfg</filename>. Make sure that you do not change the "
"<literal>exec tail -n +3 $0</literal> part at the beginning."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: filename
#: grub2.xml:545
#, no-c-format
msgid "90_persistent"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: grub2.xml:548
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"This is a special script that copies a corresponding part of the "
"<filename>grub.cfg</filename> file and outputs it back unchanged. This way "
"you can modify that part of <filename>grub.cfg</filename> directly and the "
"change survives the execution of <xref linkend=\"vle.grub2.mkconfig\"/>."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: grub2.xml:558
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"The processing sequence is set by the preceding numbers with the lowest "
"number being executed first. If scripts are preceded by the same number the "
"alphabetical order of the complete name decides the order."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: title
#: grub2.xml:566
#, no-c-format
msgid "Mapping between BIOS Drives and Linux Devices"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: secondary
#: grub2.xml:568
#, no-c-format
msgid "device.map"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: grub2.xml:569
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"In GRUB Legacy, the <filename>device.map</filename> configuration file was "
"used to derive Linux device names from BIOS drive numbers. The mapping "
"between BIOS drives and Linux devices cannot always be guessed correctly. "
"For example, GRUB Legacy would get a wrong order if the boot sequence of IDE "
"and SCSI drives is exchanged in the BIOS configuration."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: grub2.xml:576
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"&grub; avoids this problem by using device ID strings (UUIDs) or file system "
"labels when generating <filename>grub.cfg</filename>. &grub; utilities "
"create a temporary device map on the fly, which is usually sufficient, "
"particularly in the case of single-disk systems."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: grub2.xml:582
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"However, if you need to override the &grub;'s automatic device mapping "
"mechanism, create your custom mapping file <filename>/boot/grub2/device.map</"
"filename>. The following example changes the mapping to make <literal>DISK "
"3</literal> the boot disk. Note that &grub; partition numbers start with "
"<literal>1</literal> and not with <literal>0</literal> as in GRUB Legacy."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: screen
#: grub2.xml:590
#, no-c-format
